# 01 — System Overview

## What the System Does

This project turns a Waveshare ESP32-S3-POE-ETH-8DI-8DO board into a self-contained industrial monitoring and control node. The ESP32 hosts a multi-page web application entirely from its own flash memory (LittleFS). Any device on the same network — PC, tablet, phone — can open a browser and interact with the dashboard without installing any app or driver.

The system monitors eight digital inputs (sensors, limit switches, proximity sensors), controls eight digital outputs (relays, indicators), measures machine runtime/downtime/cycle time, logs data to an SD card, publishes telemetry via MQTT, polls Modbus RTU RS485 slave devices, and sends push alerts through a Telegram bot.


## Use Cases

This system is designed for light industrial and educational smart-factory scenarios:

- Machine monitoring — track whether a production machine is RUNNING or STOPPED, measure how long it has been in each state, and calculate efficiency automatically.
- Production counting — count part detections from sensors (e.g. position sensors DI4–DI6 for a conveyor start/middle/end position), measure cycle times between sensor triggers.
- Reject detection — count metal-detect triggers (DI7), alert via Telegram every N rejects.
- Remote output control — toggle relays from the web UI or from a Telegram command (`/do on 1`).
- Modbus RS485 integration — read data from PLCs, VFDs, energy meters, or other Modbus RTU slaves.
- Data logging — write timestamped CSV rows to SD card for later analysis.
- SCADA/IoT integration — publish DI/DO state changes and subscribe to DO control messages over MQTT (local or cloud broker).


## Key Components

### Hardware
| Component | Role |
|---|---|
| ESP32-S3 MCU | Dual-core 240 MHz processor; runs the web server, MQTT client, RS485 Modbus master, FreeRTOS tasks |
| 8 × Digital Inputs | Opto-isolated; connected to GPIO 4–11; active-LOW with pull-up |
| 8 × Digital Outputs | Controlled via I2C GPIO expander (PCF8574 at address 0x20); state stored as a bitmask (`outputState`) |
| Ethernet (PoE) | Primary network; auto-detected via `ETH.begin()` |
| Wi-Fi | Fallback network if Ethernet is unavailable |
| SD Card (SD_MMC) | 1-bit MMC mode on GPIO 45/47/48; stores timestamped CSV log files |
| RS485 UART | UART1 on GPIO 17 (TX) / 18 (RX) / 21 (DE/RE); Modbus RTU master |
| I2C Bus | GPIO 41 (SDA) / 42 (SCL); used for output expander |

### Software (Firmware)
| Module | Role |
|---|---|
| `WebServer` | Handles all HTTP GET/POST requests on port 80 |
| `LittleFS` | Stores web files (HTML, CSS, JS, JSON) in ESP32 internal flash |
| `PubSubClient` | MQTT client; publishes DI state changes, subscribes to DO control topics |
| `WebSocketsClient` | Used as transport layer for cloud MQTT over WebSocket/WSS |
| `ModbusMaster` | Modbus RTU master library for RS485 register polling |
| `ArduinoJson` | JSON serialisation/deserialisation for all API responses and config files |
| `UniversalTelegramBot` | Telegram Bot API client for push alerts and command handling |
| `SD_MMC` | SD card driver in 1-bit MMC mode |
| FreeRTOS Tasks | `telegramTask` (Core 0) and `rs485Task` (Core 0); main loop runs on Core 1 |

### Web Frontend
| File | Page |
|---|---|
| `index.html` | Dashboard — DI/DO state, process metrics, ESP32 health |
| `monitoring.html` | Monitoring — LED indicators, trigger counters, calculator, custom efficiency formula |
